<div class="intro">
    <h1>The Mission</h1>
    <p class="lead" style="font-size: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.4; color: var(--color-text-muted); margin-bottom: 2rem;">
        Moving from <strong>Implementation Lock-in</strong> to <strong>Protocol Interoperability</strong>.
    </p>
</div>

<div class="content-box" style="margin-bottom: 3rem;">
    <h2>The Problem: The Framework Silo</h2>
    <p>
        For too long, web development has been fragmented. We build the same low-level components—dropdowns, calendars, modals—over and over again, locked inside specific frameworks. 
    </p>
    <p>
        It is inefficient to rely on a React-specific calendar that uses a React-specific dropdown, completely incompatible with a Vue component sitting right next to it. Even worse, many of these "top-tier" libraries fail to implement the full range of UX, usability, and accessibility recommendations that are well understood but hard to get right.
    </p>
    <p>
        When we fix a usability issue in one library, it doesn't fix it for the web. It only fixes it for that silo.
    </p>

    <hr style="border: 0; border-top: 1px solid var(--color-border); margin: 3rem 0;">

    <h2>The Vision: Native Protocols</h2>
    <p>
        We believe that <strong>web-native versions of these low-level components should exist</strong>. While specific implementations may never become a single standard, the <em>protocols</em> they use can.
    </p>
    <p>
        <strong>Web Everything</strong> is a collection of specifications and implementations to fill the "holes" in the browser platform needed to build these components natively:
    </p>

    <ul style="display: grid; gap: 1.5rem; margin-top: 2rem; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(300px, 1fr));">
        <li>
            <strong>Dependency Injection (DI):</strong> A standard way to provide services and data deeply into component trees without prop drilling.
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>Scoping:</strong> A method for teams to create isolated modules without conflict, avoiding the style-isolation pitfalls of ShadowDOM for complex views.
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>Advanced Binding (Tokens):</strong> Configurable, retro-compatible binding syntaxes that don't force a single template language on developers.
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>Logic w/o Geometry (Directives):</strong> Adding dynamism to the DOM without polluting the layout with wrapper `div`s.
        </li>
    </ul>
</div>

